AP SOSC W Selected Topics in Health and Society
  3115  3.00 M  EN SEMR  01  R94Q01 
T11:30170KeeleACW 003
Aimi Hamraie Title: Disability Culture and Technology Description: Many people think of disability technologies as those that are created to normalize or rehabilitate bodies that fall outside of the norm. These technologies are made for disabled people, often by nondisabled designers and engineers. But disabled people and communities also produce, adapt, and hack technologies, not only for functional uses, but also to build community. This course will approach disability technology from the perspective of disability culture, a term that describes what happens when groups of disabled people get together to do things, whether to survive, organize politically, make art, or design a new world. We will explore disability culture through frameworks offered by the field of critical disability studies. We will also examine the uses, meanings, and frameworks of technology through the insights of the field of science and technology studies, particularly the notion of technoscience. These frameworks will guide us through explorations of built and social environments, material culture, art, media, fashion, and other dimensions of design. Course Outline
